SIMPLE: fence
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fence
<hw>Fence</hw> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. from
<ets>defence</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which fends off attack
or danger; a defense; a protection; a cover; security; shield.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us be backed with God and with the seas,⟦br⟧
Which he hath given for <qex>fence</qex> impregnable.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>fence</qex> betwixt us and the victor's wrath.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An inclosure about a field or other space, or about
any object; especially, an inclosing structure of wood, iron, or other
material, intended to prevent intrusion from without or straying from
within.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leaps o'er the <qex>fence</qex> with ease into the fold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In England a hedge, ditch, or wall, as well as a
structure of boards, palings, or rails, is called a
<xex>fence</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Locks)</fld> <def>A projection on the bolt, which
passes through the tumbler gates in locking and unlocking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Self-defense by the use of the sword; the art and
practice of fencing and sword play; hence, skill in debate and repartee.
See <er>Fencing</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Enjoy your dear wit, and gay rhetoric,⟦br⟧
That hath so well been taught her dazzing <qex>fence</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of dauntless courage and consummate skill in <qex>fence</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A receiver of stolen goods, or a place where they
are received.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Mayhew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fence month</b></col> <fld>(Forest Law)</fld>, <cd>the
month in which female deer are fawning, when hunting is prohibited.</cd>
<au>Bullokar.</au> -- <col><b>Fence roof</b></col>, <cd>a covering for
defense.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧They fitted their shields close to one another in
manner of a <xex>fence roof</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Holland.</au> --
<col><b>Fence time</b></col>, <cd>the breeding time of fish or game,
when they should not be killed.</cd> -- <col><b>Rail fence</b></col>,
<cd>a fence made of rails, sometimes supported by posts.</cd> --
<col><b>Ring fence</b></col>, <cd>a fence which encircles a large area,
or a whole estate, within one inclosure.</cd> -- <col><b>Worm
fence</b></col>, <cd>a zigzag fence composed of rails crossing one
another at their ends; -- called also <altname>snake fence</altname>, or
<altname>Virginia rail fence</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>To be on the
fence</b></col>, <cd>to be undecided or uncommitted in respect to two
opposing parties or policies.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 552 --></p>

<p><ent>Fence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fence
<hw>Fence</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fenced</conjf> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧nst)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fencing</conjf> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧n"s⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To fend off danger from; to give security to; to
protect; to guard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>fence</qex> my ear against thy sorceries.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inclose with a fence or other protection; to
secure by an inclosure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O thou wall! . . . dive in the earth,⟦br⟧
And <qex>fence</qex> not Athens.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sheepcote <qex>fenced</qex> about with olive trees.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fence the tables</b></col> <fld>(Scot. Church)</fld>,
<cd>to make a solemn address to those who present themselves to commune
at the Lord's supper, on the feelings appropriate to the service, in
order to hinder, so far as possible, those who are unworthy from
approaching the table.</cd> <au>McCheyne.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fence
<hw>Fence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a
defense; to guard one's self of anything, as against an attack; to give
protection or security, as by a fence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vice is the more stubborn as well as the more dangerous evil, and
therefore, in the first place, to be <qex>fenced</qex> against.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To practice the art of attack and defense with the
sword or with the foil, esp. with the smallsword, using the point
only.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will <qex>fence</qex> with his own shadow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, to fight or dispute in the manner of fencers,
that is, by thrusting, guarding, parrying, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>fence</qex> and push, and, pushing, loudly roar;⟦br⟧
Their dewlaps and their sides are bathed in gore.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As when a billow, blown against,⟦br⟧
Falls back, the voice with which I <qex>fenced</qex>⟦br⟧
A little ceased, but recommenced.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fenceful</ent>⟦br⟧
